The compound p-nitrosalicylic acid contains several functional groups that will affect its melting point: a carboxylic acid (COOH), a hydroxyl group (OH) attached to an aromatic ring, and a nitroso group (NO) also attached to the aromatic ring. - Hydroxyl group (OH): This group forms hydrogen bonds, which can add approximately 40 to 60 degrees to the melting point due to the increased intermolecular forces.
- Nitroso group (NO): The nitroso group is an electron-withdrawing group and enhances the stability of the molecule through resonance, which typically contributes to an increase in melting point by around 20 to 30 degrees due to stronger molecular interactions.
- Aromatic ring: The presence of an aromatic ring generally increases the melting point relative to aliphatic compounds because of the stable pi system that encourages London dispersion forces; however, we will treat this as the base structure without a specific numerical value added for this component alone.
These effects are additive, but because the compound is already highly polar and capable of forming strong hydrogen bonds and dipole-dipole interactions, the incremental increases from the hydroxyl group and nitroso group will be less pronounced than they would be in a nonpolar compound. Therefore, rather than simply adding up the numerical values, we must consider a reduced effect because of the existing strong intermolecular forces and the possibility of intramolecular hydrogen bonding between the OH and COOH groups that could slightly lower the melting point.
